    The Legacy of Nikola Tesla: A Bane & Boon?

    Nikola Tesla is one of history's most important energy-related inventors. His legacy lives on through his contributions to the design of the modern alternating current electricity supply system. Another way to interpret his legacy is through two very different companies who have adopted parts of his name: Nikola and     Tesla, one of whose owner was found guilty of fraud and faces up to 20 years in prison, while the other enjoys the riches of being the richest man in the world.

    How did Trevor Milton, former CEO of Nikola Motor Company defraud investors and the SEC to create a company worth $34 billion with a technology that didn’t exist and a vehicle that couldn’t even drive itself?

    That’s a question over which the likes of General Motors, bp and Bosch are still scratching their heads. With outrageous claims, lofty promises, a great design and a confident smile, Trevor used the power of social media to build hype around a technology which was too good to be true.

    Touted as the ‘next Elon Musk’ by major news corporations, investors who missed out on the goldmine which Tesla turned out to be were all over Nikola. This very blindfold was the primary reason Trevor was able to raise outrageous amounts of money from investors who turned a blind eye to the voice of expert engineers, scientists and technicians, all of whom were sceptical of the claims.

    While the world was dazed with the Nikola Two Electric Semi Truck rolling down a hill, it is now a concept which has rolled off the page. While Trevor took the meaning of the phrase, ‘fake it till you make it’ to a whole new level, his story raises fundamental questions of the research which goes behind making an investment.

  • Soham Shukla posted this • 1mo1mo
    Debranding: The Secret Genocide of the 21st Century

    This is a concept which has swept the corporate world by storm with some of the biggest brands in the world using this strategy in their rebranding efforts. It is a concept in which companies have discarded depth and detail within their logos as a way to conform to modern day trends and appeal to the masses.

    As seen in the visual below, companies such as     Burger King, Nissan Motor Corporation, Rolling Stone, Volkswagen AG, Warner Bros, Durex Industries and a plethora of others have shed weight, depth and shadow.

    So why has this been happening on such a global scale? The answer to that lies within three primary reasons: mobile-first design, brand maturity and fashion.

    Mobile-first design is the mouse which every brand is trying to chase. In a race to stand out amongst a stampede of brands trying to capture limited screen space while an individual scrolls through Instagram, brands have moved to a 2D look, focused on fitting their entire identity into a small digital box. This forces a lot of pixel pressure, which has pushed brands to a return to sobriety after a spasm of software induced intoxications.

    Brand maturity comes after some of these largest brands have moved on from their playful innocence which acted as the heartbeat of their early hashtag #branding . Brands such as Google and Airbnb have moved from flamboyant to flat, cartoonish to corporate, and whacky to bland as the stakes rose and they were required to professionalise.

    Fashion plays a pivotal role as company logos are as susceptible to trends as any other hashtag #design . The flood of the ‘little black dress logos’ showcases primarily that as brands such as Calvin Klein, Balmain, and Burberry debranded themselves to the likes of this classic black & white monochromatic design language.

    While many ride this wave, do you think that hashtag #debranding creates a soulless collection of coloured letters or abstract shapes devoid of any character and excitement that once persisted?
  • Soham Shukla posted this • 1mo1mo
    Rome wasn’t built in a day.

    While Ather took seven long years to develop their electric scooter, Ola, India’s leading ride-hailing service seemed to think they could do it in a year and it royally blew up in their face. Let’s have a look at when a company tries to race against time.

    In May 2020, Ola made a bold decision to acquire Etergo, an Amsterdam-based electric scooter manufacturer with the hope of riding the next big wave in the two-wheeler market. It started off with a bang, announcing its value proposition of providing a monsterous range of 180km with a top speed of 115kmph, all in addition to it a revolutionary smart screen and a sleek and stylish design. With gasoline prices off the charts, for the Indian customer, this seemed like a slice of heaven.

    In July when Ola opened pre-orders, they were the happiest kid on the block clocking in more than 1 lakh bookings equating to a revenue of Rs.1,100 crores. However, this all came crashing down not soon after.

    Starting March 2022, they started receiving complaints of their scooters catching fire, battery issues, software bugs etc. These got worse in August, when the scooter faced structural loopholes and started breaking down. Public outrage was at a peak and it was really time Ola looked into the reasons behind these shortcomings. Did Ola make one of the biggest business blunders: overpromising and under-delivering?

    However, despite all these problems, Ola became India’s top selling 2-wheeler EV in September 2022 by outselling the likes of Ather, Hero, Okinawa and Ampere. This shows the strong brand value of Ola and the trust people have in their technology. The only question is for how long will this sustain if Ola doesn’t take the appropriate steps?
